[30;1m2552 | [0m[35m            Dictionary of form {j:{(i, -tau): link_type, ...}, ...} specifying[0m
[30;1m2553 | [0m[35m            assumptions about links. This initializes the graph with entries[0m
[30;1m2554 | [0m[35m            graph[i,j,tau] = link_type. For example, graph[i,j,0] = '-->'[0m
[30;1m2555 | [0m[35m            implies that a directed link from i to j at lag 0 must exist.[0m
[30;1m2556 | [0m[35m            Valid link types are 'o-o', '-->', '<--'. In addition, the middle[0m
[30;1m2557 | [0m[35m            mark can be '?' instead of '-'. Then '-?>' implies that this link[0m
[30;1m2558 | [0m[35m            may not exist, but if it exists, its orientation is '-->'. Link[0m

[30;1m74 | [0m[35m    In the PCMCI framework, the dependency structure of a set of time series[0m
[30;1m75 | [0m[35m    variables is represented in a *time series graph* as shown in the Figure.[0m
[30;1m76 | [0m[35m    The nodes of a time series graph are defined as the variables at[0m
[30;1m77 | [0m[35m    different times and a link indicates a conditional dependency that can be[0m
[30;1m78 | [0m[35m    interpreted as a causal dependency under certain assumptions (see paper).[0m
[30;1m79 | [0m[35m    Assuming stationarity, the links are repeated in time. The parents[0m
[30;1m80 | [0m[35m    :math:`\mathcal{P}` of a variable are defined as the set of all nodes[0m
